g6pd-deficiency-hemoglobinopathiesAndHem.def:
G6PD deficiency is an X-linked recessive genetic disorder that is defined by reduced chemical activity of the G6PD enzyme.
There were a total of 8·96 million (95% UI 8·05–10·0) people born with glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase (G6PD) deficiency in 2019 and a total of 438 million (400–483) living with G6PD deficiency. G6PD deficiency was responsible for 13 000 all-ages deaths (9860–18 000) in 2019, 367 (225–568) of which were in children under 5.
g6pd-deficiency-hemoglobinopathiesAndHem.name: G6PD deficiency

g6pd-trait-hemoglobinopathiesAndHemolyti.def:
G6PD deficiency is an X-linked recessive genetic disorder that is defined by reduced chemical activity of the G6PD enzyme. G6PD trait occurs only in females when one copy of the X chromosome has a mutation in the G6PD gene.
There were a total of 18·7 million (95% UI 18·0–19·5) females born with glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase (G6PD) trait in 2019 and a total of 1·03 billion (0·998–1·07) living with G6PD trait. G6PD trait was responsible for 23 600 YLDs (15 700–34 200) in 2019.
g6pd-trait-hemoglobinopathiesAndHemolyti.name: G6PD trait

other-hemoglobinopathies-and-hemolytic-a.def:
Other haemoglobinopathies and haemolytic anaemias include a number of blood disorders including inherited and acquired haemolytic anaemias, red cell aplasia, and aplastic anaemias.
Other haemoglobinopathies and haemolytic anaemias were responsible for 27 600 all-ages deaths (95% UI 23 900–32 500) in 2019, 74 (56–97) of which were in children under 5. They caused a total of 1·69 million (1·13–2·43) YLDs in 2019.
other-hemoglobinopathies-and-hemolytic-a.name: Other hemoglobinopathies and hemolytic anemias

sickle-cell-disorders-hemoglobinopathies.def:
SCD is defined by genotype and modelled as three separate entities: 1) homozygous sickle cell and severe sickle cell/beta-thalassaemia, 2) haemoglobin (Hb) SC disease, and 3) “mild” sickle cell-beta thalassaemia.
There were a total of 605 000 people (95% UI 466 000–781 000) born with sickle cell disorders (SCD) in 2019 and a total of 5·69 million (4·54–7·10) living with SCD. SCD was responsible for 41 900 all-ages deaths (29 500–57 900) in 2019.
sickle-cell-disorders-hemoglobinopathies.name: Sickle cell disorders

sickle-cell-trait-hemoglobinopathiesAndH.def:
SCT is defined as heterozygous, or carrier, state for the sickle mutation of haemoglobin (HbS). HbC and HbD are not included in the case definition.
There were a total of 10·1 million (95% UI 8·92–11·4) people born with sickle cell trait (SCT) in 2019 and a total of 438 million (384–499) living with SCT. SCT caused a total of 2·42 million (1·58–3·54) all-ages YLDs in 2019, a 38·5% (33·9–43·3) increase since 1990.
sickle-cell-trait-hemoglobinopathiesAndH.name: Sickle cell trait

thalassemias-hemoglobinopathiesAndHemoly.def:
Thalassaemias are defined by genotype and modelled as three separate entities: 1) beta-thalassaemia major, 2) haemoglobin E/beta-thalassaemia, and 3) haemoglobin H disease (genotype = - - / - alpha), which is the most severe form of alpha thalassaemia.
There were a total of 152 000 people (95 % UI 119 000–201 000) born with thalassaemias in 2019. Thalassaemias were responsible for 10 200 all-ages deaths (8580–12 000) in 2019, 3780 (3000–4730) of which were in children under 5.
thalassemias-hemoglobinopathiesAndHemoly.name: Thalassemias

thalassemias-trait-hemoglobinopathiesAnd.def:
Thalassaemia trait is defined as heterozygous, or carrier, state for either the haemoglobin (Hb) beta mutation (beta thalassaemia trait) or E mutation (HbE trait). Milder forms of alpha thalassaemia are not included in the case definition.
There were a total of 6·34 million (95% UI 5·49–7·34) people born with thalassaemia trait in 2019 and a total of 398 million (348–462) living with it. Thalassaemia trait caused a total of 3·23 million (2·10–4·91) all-ages YLDs in 2019, a 7·3% (2·8–11·5) increase since 1990.
thalassemias-trait-hemoglobinopathiesAnd.name: Thalassemias trait
